Problem 3: Lags and Autocorrelation (20 points)

  1. (8pts) In this problem we will explore autocorrelations, which are just the correlation of a time series with itself at different lags. Before making autocorrelation plots for the NYC bike data, lets start by looking at a totally random, made up time series:
rand_ts <- rnorm(1000)

This is just 1000 random numbers from a Normal(0, 1) distribution; thus, this is simulating a time series at 1000 time points.

Using the acf() function, create an autocorrelation plot of rand_ts. The acf() function by default computes the autocorrelation for lags 0 through 30. (In general, this default value will depend on the length of the time series.) When making your autocorrelation plot for this question, display the autocorrelation for lags 0 through 500 instead. (Hint: Check the help documentation for acf to see how to change the maximum lag calculated.)

acf(rand_ts, plot = TRUE, lag.max = 500)

After youve made the plot, answer the following questions:

  • According to the confidence intervals in your plot, are any of the autocorrelations significantly different from zero? If so, which lags appear to have autocorrelations significantly different from 0?

Obviously the autocorrelation for lag = 0 is outside the confidence interval. Meanwhile, we see that there are a few random autocorrelations outside of the confidence interval.

  • If you conclude that some of the autocorrelations are significantly different from 0, give an explanation why some autocorrelations are significantly different from zero. In particular, some lags beyond lag = 0 may appear significantly different from zero; discuss why this is the case, especially considering that rand_ts is by definition a totally random time series.

The autocorrelation for lag = 0 being outside the confidence interval is totally expected: the correlation of a time series with itself will always be 1. Meanwhile, we see that there are a few random autocorrelations outside of the confidence interval. This is also totally expected: In fact, we should expect around 5% of the autocorrelations to be outside the confidence interval, because in this case we know the null hypothesis of no autocorrelation is true. This is a callback to Stat 101 material (i.e., what a confidence interval is). So, whenever youre looking at confidence intervals across long periods of time (as in the plot above), you should take any particular observation outside the confidence interval with a grain of salt.

When making your plots, please display them in a 1 x 2 grid by using par(mfrow = c(1,2)) before your two acf() lines of code.

After youve made your plots, interpret them in 1-3 sentences. Be sure to interpret your plots within the context of this dataset, which is about bike rides.

In the left-hand plot, we see that there is very high positive correlation amongst all of the lags; we can also see a slight oscillation, probably due to a weekly seasonality trend (e.g., people may ride bikes more frequently on weekends). Meanwhile, in the right-hand plot, we see a distinct seasonality trend (likely denoting the summer-winter seasonal trend we noted in Problem 2). The point of this problem was to demonstrate that it can often be helpful to make multiple autocorrelation plots. Making the maximum lag small allows us to see local trends (like weekly seasonality), but it may also be misleading (e.g., if we only made the left-hand plot, we may think that there is only positive autocorrelation); meanwhile, making the maximum lag large allows us to see global trends, and its also much easier to detect where there are positive and negative correlations. Both plots provide valuable information.

  1. (10pts) There is a whole literature on different moving averages; for example, we discussed weighted moving averages and cumulative moving averages in class. In this problem, well work with a special kind of weighted moving average thats commonly used in finance: an exponential moving average (EMA).

The idea of EMAs is to upweigh recent time periods and downweigh far away time periods when computing the moving average. In this part, you must compute the EMA in the trips_per_day dataset (i.e., ignoring usertype), and then plot that EMA on top of the raw time series. An EMA is defined in the following way:

  • For the first time period, \(t = 1\), set \(S_1 = Y_1\), where \(S_t\) is the EMA at time point \(t\), and \(Y_t\) is the outcome at time point \(t\) (in our case, n_trips).

  • For the next time periods (\(t > 1\)), define \(S_t = \alpha Y_t + (1- \alpha) S_{t-1}\) for some constant \(\alpha\). Typically, people set \(\alpha = 2/(h + 1)\), where \(h\) is the size of the window (i.e., the width you specified in Part A).

Luckily, trips_per_day should already be ordered by start.date, which will make computing the EMA easier. Below is some template code to get you started with computing the EMA; you must alter this code, based on the above methodology for computing the EMA:

#first, define EMA in the dataset
trips_per_day$ema = vector(length = nrow(trips_per_day))
#initialize the first EMA
trips_per_day$ema[1] = trips_per_day$n_trips[1]

#define alpha
alpha = 2/(14 + 1) 
#define the remaining EMAs
for(i in 2:nrow(trips_per_day)){
  trips_per_day$ema[i] = alpha*trips_per_day$n_trips[i] +
    (1-alpha)*trips_per_day$ema[i-1]
}

Note that, in the above code, we defined \(\alpha = \frac{2}{14 + 1}\), because we set width = 14 in Parts A and B. Then, within the for loop, we used the equation given in the second bullet point above.

After youve altered the above code such that ema is defined, create a plot with n_trips on the y-axis and start.date on the x-axis (similar to Problem 2B), as well as a line denoting the EMA. When making your plot, be sure that the raw time series and EMA are different colors.

Note that, when making our plot below, we made two calls to geom_line(), such that we could display the raw time series in black using just geom_line() as well as the moving average in red.

ggplot(trips_per_day, aes(x = start.date, y = n_trips)) +
geom_line() + geom_line(aes(x = start.date, y = ema), color = "red") + labs(x = "Date", y = "Number of Trips")

For this part, all you have to do is create the plot. You should end up with a moving average that looks similar to the kind of moving averages you might see for stock prices.
